{"runId":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro@2026-05-13T17-06-31-451Z","slug":"docker-firewall-setup","locale":"de","model":"openai/gpt-oss-120b:nitro","modelPath":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro","createdAt":"2026-05-13T17:06:34.554Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2015-06-06--docker-firewall-setup/index.md","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2015-06-06--docker-firewall-setup/de/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/docker-firewall-setup/de/openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro/2026-05-13T17-06-31-451Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"c90ef4cdc10616a355fa492d2d837de04342f988bf3aae83d375b181929bbba2","outputHash":"231db0dbef8b8a83e3d60f7f5409eb1b973537599e340ee9675ac873485e8d49","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.3,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"The article is a practical tutorial aimed at system administrators who run Docker on Debian‑ or Ubuntu‑based servers and need to harden the host with a firewall. It argues that a simple UFW (Uncomplicated Firewall) configuration can protect both the host and Docker containers while still allowing necessary services such as SSH, HTTP/HTTPS, DNS, and specific container ports. Key points include installing UFW and auxiliary tools, determining internal and external IPs, setting default deny policies (with a choice for outbound traffic), adding explicit allow rules for SSH (with logging and rate‑limiting), web traffic, DNS, and forwarding a public port (e.g., 8080) to a container port, then enabling the firewall safely and verifying it with nmap scans. The tone is instructional, using step‑by‑step shell commands and occasional warnings (“don’t lock yourself out”) as the primary framing device.","totalInputTokens":4024,"totalOutputTokens":891,"totalCacheReadTokens":1280,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":1507,"totalCostUsd":0.000317316,"pricingSource":"local-openrouter-estimate","telemetry":{"model":"openai/gpt-oss-120b:nitro","chunkSize":"6p","totalChunks":4,"totalInputTokens":4024,"totalOutputTokens":891,"totalCacheRead